{"cursor":"7346","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox settlement |name = Ivittuut |image_skyline =\nCryolite_mine_ivgtut_greenland.jpg |imagesize = 300px |image_caption = The\ncryolite mine in Ivittuut in 1940 |pushpin_map = Greenland\n|pushpin_label_position = left |pushpin_map_caption = Location within Greenland\n|pushpin_mapsize = 300\n| subdivision_type = State subdivision_name = subdivision_type1 = Constituent\n| country subdivision_name1 = subdivision_type2 = Municipality subdivision_name2\n| = Sermersooq subdivision_type3 = subdivision_name3 =\n|established_title = |established_date = |extinct_title = Abandoned\n|extinct_date = 1980s |timezone = UTC-03 |latd=61|latm=12|lats=30|latNS=N\n|longd=48|longm=10|longs=10|longEW=W |coordinates_display = inline,title\n|coordinates_region = GL }}\n\n'Ivittuut', formerly 'IvigtÃ»t' (Kalaallisut: \"Grassy\nPlace\" [http://www.sermersooq.gl/en/tourism_in_sermersooq/ivittuut.aspx\nSermersooq Municipality] ), is an abandoned mining town near Cape\nDesolation in southwestern Greenland. Its site is located in the modern\nSermersooq municipality on the ruins of the former Norse 'Middle Settlement'.\n\nIvittuut is one of the only locations in the world so far discovered to have\nnaturally occurring cryolite (Na 3AlF 6, sodium aluminum\nfluoride), an important agent in modern aluminum extraction.\n\nFor the former U.S. Army post and Naval base at Ivigtut, see Bluie West Seven.\nFor the former Royal Danish Navy base, see Gronnedal.\n","linknr":235,"url":"Ivigtut","recorded":1374764223,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Ivittuut&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Ivittuut&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","/wiki/Ivittuut","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTo